data.title: Koch feels support at Olympic Trials send off

data.text:
Jim Clark

Women's Track & Field 6/28/2016

Koch feels support at Olympic Trials send off

CEDARVILLE, Ohio - NCAA champion Carsyn Koch departed for the U.S. Olympic Team Trials in Eugene, Oregon today amid cheers from hundreds of Yellow Jacket supporters.

The reigning Division II 800 meter indoor and outdoor champion is traveling with CU Track & Field Head Coach Jeff Bolender along with his wife, Sharie, a former standout Lady Jacket distance runner.

Koch, a sophomore from Washburn, Maine, competes in the women's 800 meter prelims on July 1. Competition in the event is scheduled to begin at 7:45 p.m. EDT.

Athletic Director Dr. Alan Geist welcomed the crowd gathered in front of the Callan Athletic Center. Bolender provided a brief update before Koch thanked the group for coming out along with several comments.

Assistant Athletic Director for Compliance Christopher Cross closed the time in prayer before Koch left campus with the Bolenders to the applause of the crowd.

The women's 800 meter semifinals are slated for July 2 at 2:43 p.m. EDT with the finals on July 4 at 8:51 p.m.

Koch met the Trials qualifying mark with a 2:02.39 effort on May 1 in the Payton Jordan Invitational at Stanford University (Calif.). It's the fastest outdoor women's 800 time in NCAA Division II history.
